{"type":"message","id":"d1c4dbc7","parentId":"86f46319","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:42:40.243Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me set up the cron job to use a smarter approach. The key issue is that the old cron job was reporting the same email every hour because it didn't track state. I need to:\n\n1. Track the last reported email ID\n2. Only report new emails\n\nThe script I created handles tracking, but the cron job calls it via an isolated agentTurn. I should set up a smarter cron that runs the script and only notifies if there's a new email.\n\nActually, the best approach would be to have the cron job run the script, and only send a message if there's a new email. But with isolated agentTurn sessions, I need to handle this differently.\n\nLet me think about this... The cron job is an isolated agentTurn that runs every hour. When it fires, it sends a message to the agent which then checks email and reports. The issue is the agent always reports - it doesn't know what was already reported.\n\nThe fix: The agent needs to check the tracking file and only report if the email is new.\n\nBut I just deleted the cron job entirely! Let me set it back up with the smart logic.\n\nLet me recreate the cron job with the smart tracking built into the agentTurn prompt.\n","thinkingSignature":"26b4afae8a43fd367e1362b0af5e69567e8cdb4b83e7ccd271b3e24facb3234f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ccpf2kmyxdep_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"rm -f /tmp/emmy_last_email_id && echo \"Track file reset\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":454,"output":286,"cacheRead":29504,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30244,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777686126690,"responseId":"0644897dba83564cf9e4a73778cc208d"}}
