{"type":"message","id":"da4e6406","parentId":"2699a782","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:44:24.515Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ah, I see the problem! The script echoes \"NEW_EMAIL_FOUND\" to stdout, but the EMAIL_ID comparison is comparing `$EMAIL_ID` (which is `19de5e6b3162ed52`) with `NO_UNREAD`. But after the first run, the track file contains `19de5e6b3162ed52`, and on the second run `$EMAIL_ID` is also `19de5e6b3162ed52`, so they should match and it should exit 0...\n\nWait, let me look at the logic again:\n\n```bash\nif [ \"$EMAIL_ID\" = \"$LAST\" ] || [ \"$LAST\" = \"NO_UNREAD\" ]; then\n  exit 0\nfi\n```\n\nAfter run 1: EMAIL_ID = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\", LAST = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\" → they match → should exit 0\nAfter run 2: EMAIL_ID = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\", LAST = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\" → they match → should exit 0\n\nBut the test shows it outputs \"NEW_EMAIL_FOUND\" on run 2 too... Let me check the `tail -1` part. The output of `gog email search` has a header line AND a data line. `tail -1` should get just the data line.\n\nBut wait - the first echo \"$EMAIL_ID\" > \"$TRACK_FILE\" writes to the file, but the conditional check happens BEFORE that line. Let me trace through:\n\nRun 1:\n- RESULT = data line (no header because of tail -1)\n- EMAIL_ID = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\"\n- LAST = \"\" (file doesn't exist)\n- [ \"$EMAIL_ID\" = \"$LAST\" ] → \"\" = \"19de5...\" → false\n- [ \"$LAST\" = \"NO_UNREAD\" ] → \"\" = \"NO_UNREAD\" → false\n\n\n- Both conditions fail, so we write the email ID to the track file and output \"NEW_EMAIL_FOUND\"\n\nRun 2:\n- RESULT = data line\n- EMAIL_ID = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\"\n- LAST = \"19de5e6b3162ed52\"\n- [ \"$EMAIL_ID\" = \"$LAST\" ] → true → exit 0\n\nThis should work, but the test shows otherwise. Let me verify the actual file content after run 2 to see what's really stored there.\n\nWait, I'm checking the track file content with a separate cat command, which should work. But something's off. Let me look at the script more carefully - I think I see the issue now.\n\nLooking at the conditional logic: on run 2, the email ID matches what's stored, so it should exit 0 before reaching the NEW_EMAIL_FOUND echo. The fact that it's still printing suggests the comparison isn't working as expected. Let me verify the actual value in the track file after the first run - it should be \"19de5e6b3162ed52\", which means on run 2 when we read it back and compare, they should be equal and trigger the exit. The file is being written correctly with the email ID, so the comparison logic must be failing somehow. I'm realizing the test script always echoes \"Would notify\" regardless of the check script's exit code, so that doesn't actually validate anything. I should verify whether the script itself is exiting with code 0 or something else.\n","thinkingSignature":"f4233b9ca0dd4e446e239ed82d5d6650308d14541e427b4c7b9538e27eafdaa4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lplotepl21aq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Proper test - use exit code\nrm -f /tmp/emmy_last_email_id /tmp/emmy_email_log.txt\n\necho \"=== Test 1 ===\"\n/tmp/emmy_email_check_agent.sh\necho \"Exit code: $?\"\n\necho \"=== Test 2 ===\"\n/tmp/emmy_email_check_agent.sh\necho \"Exit code: $?\"\n\necho \"=== Test 3 ===\"\n/tmp/emmy_email_check_agent.sh\necho \"Exit code: $?\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":187,"output":853,"cacheRead":31680,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32720,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777686240924,"responseId":"064489e0643ab0b866b429ca72f4e44f"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a711fcd7","parentId":"da4e6406","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:44:27.458Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_lplotepl21aq_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"=== Test 1 ===\nNEW_EMAIL_FOUND\nExit code: 0\n=== Test 2 ===\nExit code: 0\n=== Test 3 ===\nExit code: 0"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":2909,"aggregated":"=== Test 1 ===\nNEW_EMAIL_FOUND\nExit code: 0\n=== Test 2 ===\nExit code: 0\n=== Test 3 ===\nExit code: 0","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777686267458}}
{"type":"message","id":"8814a382","parentId":"a711fcd7","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:44:36.956Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, the exit code from my script was 0 in all cases, which is expected since the script itself exits with 0. But the output \"NEW_EMAIL_FOUND\" only appeared in Test 1. The issue was with my test piping - I was using `&&` to check exit code but the script's exit code was always 0 (the script's final exit is 0).\n\nActually wait - the output \"NEW_EMAIL_FOUND\" only showed in Test 1, and Tests 2 and 3 had no output, which means the script IS working correctly - it's staying silent after the first run. The exit code checking was just confused because I was using `&&` which runs the next command if the previous exited with 0 - and my script always exits 0.\n\n\nEverything's working as intended. I'll message Bobby to let him know the hourly email check is back up and running, but now it's smart enough to only ping him when there's actually a new email rather than repeating the same notification.\n","thinkingSignature":"8973c8120d15e66eb70c8cd101b59ed6c51565558473ada57bb497cd68df11b7"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\nFixed. The script works correctly now — stays silent on repeat checks, only notifies on new emails.\n\nRestored the hourly check but smarter this time. Only bothers you when there's actually something new. 👍"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":230,"output":247,"cacheRead":31808,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32285,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777686267463,"responseId":"064489fb2e2ad794e0c2e4e336784e12"}}
